<subSubSection id="C32660E89E1C9F0CFF0DFF1616931A2C" pageId="19" pageNumber="370" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8333639E1C9F0CFF0DFF1616931A2C" blockId="19.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="19" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis id="B948EF719E1C9F0CFF0DFF1613771BE4" bold="true" box="[199,315,188,213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="370">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described from 
<collectingRegion id="49F8FD819E1C9F0CFD75FF16116F1BE4" box="[703,803,188,213]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="19" pageNumber="370">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32B73F39E1C9F0CFCE5FF16113E1BE4" box="[815,882,188,213]" name="China" pageId="19" pageNumber="370">China</collectingCountry>
by Li and Wang (2002) based on four male and two female specimens. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C48E09E1C9F0CFD98FF4A10A11BC9" authority="Li" authorityName="Li" box="[594,749,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="B948EF719E1C9F0CFD98FF4A10851BC9" box="[594,713,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="370">S. apicalis</emphasis>
Li
</taxonomicName>
, but is easily distinguishable from the latter in the shape of subgenital plate, and by the aedeagal shaft and connective processes with serrated dorsal margins.
</paragraph>
